{
  "answer": "**Cynewulf's *Elene*** centrally addresses Saint Elene (Helena, mother of Constantine), portraying her as the heroic protagonist who leads a quest to find the True Cross. She interrogates Jewish scholars at length, commands actions, and drives the narrative through her speeches and resolve.[^1][^2]\n\n**Cynewulf's *Juliana*** is a hagiographic poem centered on Saint Juliana of Nicomedia, a virgin martyr. She rejects a pagan suitor, endures torture, interrogates and binds a devil in her cell (who speaks extensively), and delivers final exhortations before her beheading.[^3][^4]\n\n**\"The Wife's Lament\"** (Chapter 3 of *Old English Elegies*) is a first-person lament spoken by an unnamed exiled wife, who recounts her betrayal by her husband, her isolation in a cave under an oak tree, and her enduring grief.[^5]\n\nNo other works in the corpus feature named female speakers or centrally address female figures in this manner. The remaining 34 works (e.g., smṛtis by male sages like Manu, Urdu poetry by Iqbal and Ghalib, French political treatises by Comte and Dunoyer) lack such elements.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-534627).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-7b1c1f).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-ceda92).\n[^4]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-a370d7).\n[^5]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 3 [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-23cb49).",
